  title="5 Warning Signs Your Chimney Needs Cleaning Right Now"
  description="Your chimney won't send you a calendar invite. But it does give clear warning signs when it needs attention. Here are the five you shouldn't ignore."
  publishDate="April 2026"
  readTime="4 min"
>
  <p>Most Melbourne homeowners don't think about their chimney until something goes wrong. The problem is that by the time the obvious signs appear — smoke filling the room, a struggling fire — you've already been operating with a risky level of buildup for a while.</p>

  <p>Here are the five signs that your chimney needs cleaning, from the subtle to the serious.</p>

  <h2>1. Smoke Is Coming Back Into the Room</h2>

  <p>This is the most obvious one. If you light the fire and smoke starts rolling out of the firebox into your living room instead of going up the chimney, something is blocking the airflow. That could be a bird's nest, a significant creosote buildup, a collapsed section of flue, or simply a chimney that's too dirty to draw properly.</p>

  <p>Don't keep lighting the fire and hoping it improves — this is a ventilation problem that needs to be resolved before you use the fireplace again. Carbon monoxide from a poorly venting fire is colourless, odourless and dangerous.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p>If smoke is coming into the room consistently, stop using the fireplace until the chimney has been inspected and cleaned.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>2. The Fire Burns Sluggishly or Won't Stay Lit</h2>

  <p>A well-functioning chimney creates a strong updraft that pulls air into the firebox, feeding the fire and drawing smoke up and out. When the flue is partially blocked or heavily coated with creosote, that draft is reduced — and the fire feels weak, difficult to start, or keeps dying down despite having plenty of fuel.</p>

  <p>If you're going through more kindling than usual trying to get a fire going, or if the fire burns flat and unenthusiastically, the flue is likely the problem, not the wood.</p>

  <h2>3. There's a Persistent Burnt Smell When the Fire Isn't Lit</h2>

  <p>A lingering, oily or smoky smell in the room — especially on humid days or during rain — is often a sign of heavy creosote buildup in the flue. Creosote is a sticky, tar-like residue that accumulates from burning wood, and when it gets wet it releases a distinctive acrid odour.</p>

  <p>If your living room smells faintly of a campfire on a warm afternoon in January when the fire hasn't been used since August, that's creosote — and it needs to come out.</p>

  <h2>4. You Can See Heavy Black Soot Around the Firebox</h2>

  <p>Some soot around the firebox is normal. But if you're seeing heavy, flaky black deposits — especially on the lintel, mantel or the wall above the fireplace — that's a sign the fire has been burning poorly and blowing soot back into the room rather than venting it up the chimney.</p>

  <p>Excessive soot staining outside the firebox almost always means restricted airflow, which leads back to the same answer: the flue needs to be cleaned.</p>

  <h2>5. It's Been More Than 12 Months Since the Last Clean</h2>

  <p>This one isn't a visible symptom — it's a timing issue. Even if your fire seems to be drawing well and you haven't noticed anything unusual, a chimney that's been used regularly through a Melbourne winter accumulates enough creosote to warrant annual cleaning.</p>

  <p>Creosote builds up in layers, and in its more advanced stages it can form a hard, glassy coating on the inside of the flue that's significantly harder to remove and significantly more dangerous. Catching it early — at the annual clean stage — is far easier than dealing with Stage 3 creosote buildup later.</p>

  <h2>What To Do If You've Spotted Any of These Signs</h2>

  <p>If one or more of these sounds familiar, the chimney needs to be inspected and cleaned before you use it again. This isn't a job for a can of spray and a YouTube video — a professional chimney sweep has the brushes, rods, inspection equipment and experience to do the job properly and tell you honestly what they found.</p>

  <p>In Melbourne, the busy booking period for chimney sweeps is May and June — right when everyone suddenly remembers their chimney as the cold arrives. If you're reading this in autumn, book now and you'll be able to get a time that suits you rather than waiting in a queue with a fireplace you can't use.</p>
